Japanese, Australian Stock Futures Rise on U.S. Earnings, Oil

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-04-20T23:22:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-20/japan-australia-stock-futures-rise-as-apple-s-profit-doubles-oil-gains.html
Japanese and Australian  stock
futures  advanced after U.S. companies including  Apple Inc. (AAPL) 
reported increased profits and oil prices surged, signaling the
global economic recovery is accelerating.  American depositary receipts of  Sony Corp. (6758) , Japan’s biggest
electronics exporter, gained 1.2 percent from the closing share
price yesterday in Tokyo.  Mitsubishi Corp. (8058) , the country’s No. 1
commodities trader, rose 1.4 percent after crude and metal
prices gained. ADRs of  Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL) , Australia’s
second-largest oil producer, climbed 1.4 percent.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,675 in Chicago yesterday, compared with 9,610
in Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,710 in
Osaka at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on  Australia ’s S&P/ASX
200 Index rose 1 percent today.  “U.S. companies, especially tech stocks, are doing well,
and that’s helping to instill confidence,” said Mitsushige
Akino, who oversees about $600 million in assets in Tokyo at
Ichiyoshi Investment Management Co. “Investors are looking to
take a little bit more risk.”  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index rose 0.5 percent
today after Apple reported profit that almost doubled. The
world’s largest technology company by market value announced
earnings after the close of trading in  New York .  Higher oil and metal prices boosted commodity producers.
Crude for June delivery climbed $3.17 to settle at $111.45 a
barrel yesterday in New York, the biggest increase in more than
a month. The London Metal Exchange Index of six metals including
copper and aluminum jumped 2.1 percent.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 0.6 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with gains of 5.8 percent by the  S&P
500  and of 1.2 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in
the Asian benchmark are valued at 13.2 times estimated earnings
on average as of the last close, compared with 13.6 times for
the S&P 500 and 11.2 times for the Stoxx 600.  To contact the reporters on this story:
